r the toxin’s potent neurotoxic effects and a ‘B’ subunit that facilitates its entry into nerve cells. The ‘A’ subunit binds to receptors on nerve cells, initiating a cascade of events that ultimately disrupts normal nerve function.\n\nThe mechanism of action is remarkably similar to that of botulinal neurotoxins, although tetanus toxin is significantly more potent. Both toxins share a common ‘A’ subunit that binds to acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction, causing paralysis.  However, the duration and severity of paralysis caused by tetanus toxin are generally longer and more severe than those induced by botulinal neurotoxins.\n\nTreatment for tetanus typically involves supportive care and administration of antitoxin, although the development of effective antitoxins has been challenging. Immunization with tetanus toxoid, a weakened form of the toxin, is a highly effective preventative measure against tetanus.  Vaccination stimulates the production of antibodies that can neutralize the toxin if exposure occurs.\n\nIn summary, tetanus toxin is a significant neurotoxin produced by *Clostridium tetani* that causes tetanus through its disruption of neuromuscular transmission, leading to sustained muscle contraction and a range of debilitating symptoms. Its similarities to botulinal neurotoxins highlight the evolutionary relatedness of these powerful toxins."}, "metrics": {"attempted_request_count": 1, "successful_response_count": 0, "failed_response_count": 0, "responses_with_tokens": 1, "prompt_tokens": 177, "completion_tokens": 435, "total_tokens": 612, "compute_duration_seconds": 113.43442916870117, "streaming_responses": 0, "retries": 0, "requests_with_retries": 0}}}